05398nam a22009495i 9780674067844DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2012    mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740678447 a10.4159/harvard.97806740678442doi  a(DE-B1597)177957  a(OCoLC)840444832  a(OCoLC)959596663  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aLIT0041302bisacsh04a843.912211 aHägglund, Martin, eauthor.10aDying for Time :bProust, Woolf, Nabokov /cMartin Hägglund, Martin Hägglund. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00t Frontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction Of Chronolibido -- tChapter 1. Memory: Proust -- tChapter 2. Trauma: Woolf -- tChapter 3. Writing: Nabokov -- tChapter 4. Reading: Freud, Lacan, Derrida -- tConclusion: Binding Desire -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMarcel Proust, Virginia Woolf, and Vladimir Nabokov transformed the art of the novel in order to convey the experience of time. Nevertheless, their works have been read as expressions of a desire to transcend time-whether through an epiphany of memory, an immanent moment of being, or a transcendent afterlife. Martin Hägglund takes on these themes but gives them another reading entirely. The fear of time and death does not stem from a desire to transcend time, he argues. On the contrary, it is generated by the investment in temporal life. From this vantage point, Hägglund offers in-depth analyses of Proust's Recherche, Woolf's Mrs. Dalloway, and Nabokov's Ada. Through his readings of literary works, Hägglund also sheds new light on topics of broad concern in the humanities, including time consciousness and memory, trauma and survival, the technology of writing and the aesthetic power of art. Finally, he develops an original theory of the relation between time and desire through an engagement with Freud and Lacan, addressing mourning and melancholia, pleasure and pain, attachment and loss. Dying for Time opens a new way of reading the dramas of desire as they are staged in both philosophy and literature.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aDesire in literature. 0aPsychoanalysis and literature. 0aTime in literature. 70(DE-601)1042977270(DE-588)4067461-7aZeit2gnd 70(DE-601)1043537590(DE-588)4124854-5aErzähltechnik2gnd 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh1 aHägglund, Martin, eauthor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2012z9783110288995oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE ENGLISH LINGUISTICS AND LITERATURE 2012z978311028890208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET LINGUISTIK UND LITERATURWISSENSCHAFT  2012z9783110288896oZDB-23-DGA08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP Complete eBook Package 2011-2014z978311037488908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package 2012z978311037491908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045951708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066256640uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.9780674067844423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674067844.jpg  a978-3-11-028890-2  E-BOOK PACKAGE ENGLISH LINGUISTICS AND LITERATURE 2012b2012  a978-3-11-037488-9  HUP Complete eBook Package 2011-2014  a978-3-11-037491-9  HUP eBook Package 2012b2012  a978-3-11-044220-5  HUP eBook Package Backlist 2005-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-0